segments.text: Thank you.
So when did you officially become a business major?
Sophomore year?
During the sophomore year, I made a decision.
I don't recall if it was during the sophomore year before it was changed or before it was changed.
But I can remember June being very business specific.
And your major, specific major, was management?
Yes.
All right.
Who over in there, who were some advisors, counselors, teachers?
I had a... See?
Yes.
That's my favorite.
Cool.
Cool.
During your undergraduate days, what did you and your buddies think were the expected rules of classroom behavior and attendance and so forth?
I think you've got to think about your own territory in the future.
I learned early on that if I was going to have
I can say that depending on the future, and I made every effort to attend every class, but I did not cut a lot of time.
And I did have a few friends that did, and most of those didn't make it out, didn't make it through.
Again, I think at the end of that four years, I can remember taking specific courses, I can remember taking courses further into my business direction that they were not easy, and they
They didn't necessarily try to make it easy.
They were just trying to see if you had the skill to do that.
And I did, and I got, ultimately got out of that with about three points, just two eights to three points, something like that, high two to three.
And I was proud of that because I was number 13 and I was able to get out of that.
During the summers, did you have any particular summer jobs that related to your later career?
I worked two summers at the San Antonio International Airport delivering air freight.
And I predominantly did baggage.
And it's kind of neat because that's just when they started hijacking, started, I guess, late 60s, early 70s.
And they were already making security and getting out.
And I was able to drive.
Did that help to draw you toward...
I would say it kept my attitude in mind.
Let's see.
Was the MSC important to you?
Why?
Describe your role.
I lived to go from there, but I didn't do that.
If I didn't have a girlfriend...
Was the expansion finished during your days?
Were you a part of any, member of any of the MSC activities?
Yeah, I was one year, I didn't see you, but they had a, they had like a, for lack of a better term, like a
During your days at A&M, did it matter where a student came from geographically?
Racially or economically?
among your acquaintances, was there a variety of...
Were you, did you participate in any religious activities?
And that was a year also when you don't have a question.
And I found it a real good time to be in the legislature.
And I used the office capital, although it was a file.
And the dealer was always nice to see me, but I couldn't say anything.
That's the third time it's required.
And it's even pretty, so I wasn't here for a living.
But it just, you know, you see everything now that you think of.
When you went to All Faith Chapel, what did you do?
So you would go in and sit?
You didn't read.
Did you grow up in a church-related family?
I did.
We were never seen in the morning, but we would go out.
Let's go back to some specific A&M things.
Describe court trips.
Most of the court trips I remember when we stayed
Most times, there's a group somewhere, and we would have dates that we would, you know, not be one of the student houses, but maybe one of the student cities.
And we have, you know, about 15 of us stay in there.
And a lot of us have had dates.
You know, the dates must stay in the middle part of the house.
I mean, we tell them to take it to you.
There were so much more things to come.
I'm sure there was some legal matters, you know, but it just wasn't that way.
And we just couldn't do that.
Now, where did you all get those groups of dates?
A lot of it was one of them.
Who arranged them?
You trust anybody.
Somebody was going to trust you.
It really wasn't warranty.
It was probably 80% of the time.
They weren't necessarily the right people, but they were.
You had to find them.
You knew you had to find them.
That's what it was.
Did you or anyone else you know ever have an awkward experience when it came time after an Aggie touchdown to kiss the date?
Yeah, probably most of his blind dates it wasn't awkward.
He would get kind of to a quick peck or he would go to the park when he was in the three-yard line and he'd find someone.
Mm-hmm.
Did y'all ever have a moose pot or a beast bucket?
You put a little money in the pot and whoever had the worst date got the money?
Y'all didn't do that?
Did you have a favorite place as you look back on it now for court trips?
Did you enjoy
one place more than others
Do you remember it as you think back on court trips?
Do you have a positive feel about them?
Were you all treated pleasantly?
I don't remember any of it.
And when you hitchhiked, say, to Dallas.
San Antonio.
Where did you start at A&M?
Where did you catch the ride first?
Well, I hitchhiked to Washington, so I have to remember that.
I had another buddy that went about a third of the time trying to do it.
And so we would show him up.
But I can remember one time when he and I showed up.
We got back, had those in front of us.
And it must have been 10 to 11 o'clock at night.
We just got back.
We just got back.
We just got back.
And we took another like three people to get us home early.
But usually we got back at the first five to six.
Did you ever have any bad experiences?
I haven't yet encountered one.
And am I correct in guessing that quite often you ended up riding with another aggie that you might not have otherwise known before?
Oh, no, but I was meaning that it might be by accident two Aggies might get picked up by the same person.
Oh, yeah, that happens.
If you're an A&M person and you're going down the road and you see a guy in uniform, a guy with an A&M cap or a sister's sweater, there would be a question.
Would you be picking up people on the road?
All right, the student organizations, which ones had the highest prestige?
Band, singing cadets?
Fish drill team.
What about Yoli?
Let's see, that car that you brought that freshman year, you didn't keep it long?
So you didn't have a car then for a good while?
All right, now, coeds began to increase in number while you were there.
What did you and your buddies think about that?
And you and your buddies, I'm assuming, did not think of those coeds as high-priority choices for dates.
Was that generally true among the Corps members you knew?
Were there any women in the Corps yet at that point?
They just started, like, in our junior year, it seems like, the Navy and the Marines.
I know that the Navy was set up.
And I don't remember the numbers, but at the end of the quad, they were the first one we left.
And that was kind of in there.
That was the non-airport, non-army guys.
So, like, you just went elsewhere to be free.
When you came, Earl Rutter was president.
Did you and your buddies have any image of him, any feeling?
What did you all think about Earl Rutter?
You know, I didn't think anything of him.
He was so different from my everyday life.
And I see today it seems like
He's followed and succeeded by Jack Williams, who was president when you graduated.
Did you and your buddies have any
Yes.
Yes.
The student leaders who worked with Dr. Williams nicknamed him quickly Smiling Jack because he had a perpetual smile.
Did you have much interaction in the community?
Did you go to many places in Bryan College Station?
Where did you and your buddies go to have a good time on a Saturday night if you stayed there?
If somebody wanted to go get beer, where was that?
In the dorm?
No, it's not bothering me.
I didn't want to bother you.
Was Whiskey Bridge still a reality?
You can buy alcohol in Brazos County.
And that little building has just been torn down within the last year and a half.
And I've used that phrase two or three times on today's students.
They have no idea what I'm talking about.
They say it's a different era.
It was a little bitty country, I'll call it a primitive country convenience store.
It was an old farmer, you know, an old local guy, and that was by far the closest place since Brazos County was dry to hard liquor at that time.

Well, I can remember us having an outfit at 10, three or four times, or five or six times, where we went out to Whiskey Bridge, and, like, it was still light, and we went out there and started drinking this drunk beer, and we would drop all the animals and go inside, and you could really,
All right, what else would people drink other than beer and whiskey?
All right.
And what I'm meaning is that all these sophisticated mixed drinks were, that wasn't part of it.
All right.
Then in terms of smoking, cigarettes, occasionally a cigar.
Now, how much did you and your buddies know then about marijuana, cocaine, heroin?
Very little.
I've seen a few of us do it a few times about marijuana.
Where did it come from?
Where did somebody buy it?
Did you even know the words cocaine and heroin?
We're talking about fun things and so forth.
How often did you and your buddies go to anything in Bryan or College Station off campus?
Describe the bonfire routine during your era.
Did you work on it?
Describe that.
It was something that it seemed like the very first part of bonfire you were required to go out and
I can remember being real cold and real wet.
I can remember a couple of buddies that absolutely just cut school food.
That's all there is.
And in retrospect, they've worked that.
So you were in the cutting room?
Correct.
Using axes or chainsaws?
Thank you.
What else does bonfire mean?
You said words again.
My theory is it's the inclusiveness.
That come on everybody.
Nothing else matters about income, last name, or anything else.
Fish camp, field practice, muster, bonfire, elephant walk, the marching before a football game.
Yeah.
Does any silver taps in your memory have special meaning to you?
No, but I can remember one silver tap.
You're saying it bothered your heart, your feelings later.
That's what I thought you meant.
Did you or any of your buddies cheat?
I call it cheating.
After silver taps, go back and turn on the lights and do anything?
No.
and think how important this next Silver Caps will be.
